": {\n    "dbpedia": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260423_103054_games/schema-matching/dbpedia.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260423_103054_games/normalization/attempt_1/dbpedia.csv",\n      "row_count": 46580,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "releaseYear": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%d",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "developer": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "platform": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    },\n    "metacritic": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260423_103054_games/schema-matching/metacritic.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260423_103054_games/normalization/attempt_1/metacritic.csv",\n      "row_count": 20494,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "releaseYear": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%d",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "developer": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "criticScore": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "userScore": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    },\n    "sales": {\n      "input_path": "output/runs/20260423_103054_games/schema-matching/sales.csv",\n      "output_path": "output/runs/20260423_103054_games/normalization/attempt_1/sales.csv",\n      "row_count": 7877,\n      "id_column": "id",\n      "spec_applied": {\n        "releaseYear": {\n          "output_type": "datetime",\n          "date_format": "%Y-%m-%d",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "developer": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "publisher": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "platform": {\n          "strip_whitespace": true,\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "criticScore": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        },\n        "userScore": {\n          "output_type": "string",\n          "on_failure": "keep"\n        }\n      },\n      "list_columns_applied": []\n    }\n  },\n  "warnings": [],\n  "acceptance_gate": {\n    "requested": false,\n    "request": {},\n    "pending": {}\n  },\n  "reverted_to_original": false,\n  "created_at": "2026-04-23T10:31:12.838086"\n}\n    \n        Create evaluation code that:\n        - Uses the correct fusion strategy\n        - Loads the fused output\n        - Loads the gold standard evaluation set (validation in sealed mode, otherwise test)\n        - Prints structured evaluation metrics\n        - Prints chosen evaluation functions in a compact one-line summary\n        - If helper modules are imported from local files (e.g., list_normalization), use a robust fallback import pattern that works from output/code execution context.\n        - Does NOT require exact matching everywhere by default.\n\n        EVALUATION ROBUSTNESS RULES (MANDATORY):\n- Use validation-set representation as the normalization target for evaluation.\n- Normalize fused and gold columns to the SAME representation before evaluating.\n- For country-like columns: DO NOT call normalize_country or any country normalization function.\n  The pipeline normalization node already ensures fused and gold values use the same country format.\n  Applying normalize_country in evaluation DESTROYS correct matches by converting to a different format.\n  Simply use tokenized_match for country columns, same as other text fields.\n- For free-text/list-like columns, avoid strict exact comparisons unless values are canonical identifiers.\n  Prefer tokenized_match with an explicit threshold (for example 0.7-0.9) instead of exact-only semantics.\n- If using set-based comparison on textual lists, first canonicalize list elements consistently across fused and gold.\n- Choose the right evaluation function per attribute type:\n  * tokenized_match: names, titles, labels, artists, text fields (handles word reordering like "The Beatles" vs "Beatles, The")\n  * year_only_match: dates and year columns (releaseYear, founded, publish_year) — keep values as STRINGS,\n    do NOT convert to pd.to_datetime() or pd.to_numeric() before evaluation. year_only_match extracts\n    the year component from string representations directly.\n  * set_equality_match: list-like columns (tracks, genres, categories)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: durations, prices, ratings, scores (use reasonable tolerance —\n    for user ratings/scores use tolerance=1.0, for critic scores use tolerance=5.0,\n    for durations use tolerance appropriate to the unit)\n  * numeric_tolerance_match: also use for year/count columns stored as floats (e.g. publish_year, page_count) —\n    cast both fused and gold values to int before comparison to avoid 274.0 != 274 mismatches\n  * exact_match: IDs, codes, boolean fields\n- If the gold set does NOT contain a column (i.e. it is absent, all-null, or all-whitespace), do NOT evaluate that column.\n  Only evaluate columns that are present and contain meaningful non-empty values in BOTH the fused and gold datasets.\n  Before registering an evaluation function for a column, check: gold_df[col].dropna().str.strip().replace(\'\', pd.NA).dropna()\n  — if the result is empty, skip that column entirely.\n- IMPORTANT: For columns that appear to be nested sub-fields (they share a repeated prefix pattern like\n  "tracks_track_name", "tracks_track_duration", "tracks_track_position"), these are typically derived from\n  XML nested elements and are structurally difficult to evaluate accurately. If such columns consistently\n  show very low accuracy (<20%) in early evaluation attempts, DROP them from evaluation in subsequent\n  attempts — they waste investigation cycles on structural artifacts rather than genuine fusion errors.\n  Focus evaluation on top-level scalar attributes that directly correspond to gold set columns.\n- IMPORTANT: Before evaluation, coerce numeric-like columns (publish_year, page_count, year, count, rating, score)\n  to a consistent type in BOTH fused and gold DataFrames. Common pattern:\n    for col in numeric_cols:\n        df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors=\'coerce\')\n        if df[col].dropna().apply(lambda x: float(x).is_integer()).all():\n            df[col] = df[col].astype(\'Int64\')  # nullable int avoids 274.0 vs 274 mismatches\n  This prevents false mismatches from float vs int representation differences.\n- If the fused output contains an "eval_id" column, try fused_id_column="eval_id" first.\n  However, if eval_id coverage is low (many gold IDs not found), build your own mapping:\n  For each gold record ID, search the fused _fusion_sources column to find which fused row contains that ID.\n  Use ast.literal_eval() to parse _fusion_sources (it\'s a Python list as string).\n  This handles cases where clusters contain multiple records from the same source and\n  the pre-computed eval_id picked a different one than the gold set expects.\n        \n            Evaluation reasoning from prior pipeline run:\n            {\n  "action": "decide",\n  "diagnosis": "The primary actionable defect is in fusion logic, specifically the name attribute being fused with the wrong resolver. The pipeline currently uses maximum for name, which is a numeric-oriented resolver and is producing an entirely null name column (100% null, 0% accuracy) despite all three sources having 100% non-null names and metacritic matching the validation set exactly 65% of the time. This explains the catastrophic regression of name_accuracy from 40% to 0%. Matching is not the best next fix because current evidence shows blocking recall issues are absent, correspondences are non-empty, matching F1 is already high (~0.86-0.89), and most other attributes improved substantially in the current iteration. Some residual platform/releaseYear/userScore errors are structurally limited and likely due to remaining wrong links, but the largest recoverable loss right now is the broken name fusion rule. Protected attributes developer, publisher, ESRB, and criticScore are already above 90% and should not be changed.",\n  "next_node": "pipeline_adaption",\n  "reasoning": "The highest-impact improvable issue is name. This is not a normalization problem because source names are already non-null and in the same target format style as the validation set; the failure is that the fusion stage chooses/produces no value. This is also not primarily a blocking problem because correspondence files are present and blocking probes found no recall issues. Although cluster diagnostics show some ambiguity, changing matching first would be lower leverage than fixing the obviously broken name resolver. In pipeline_adaption we can safely replace the name fuser without touching well-performing attributes. Source-vs-validation comparison already shows the best direction: prefer metacritic over sales over dbpedia for name. Since 16 attributes are above 85%, recommendations should be narrowly targeted to avoid regressions.",\n  "ceiling_assessment": "With the current matching structure, overall accuracy should be able to rise from 0.75 toward the reported ~0.888 ceiling. The biggest immediate gain is recovering name from 0% toward roughly the metacritic-aligned range; a realistic short-term outcome after fixing only name fusion is an overall improvement of about 0.08-0.13. Platform/releaseYear/userScore appear near their current structural ceiling unless matching is revisited later.",\n  "recommendations": [\n    {\n      "attribute": "name",\n      "issue": "The pipeline uses maximum for a text field, and the fused name column is entirely null even though all sources provide non-null names. This is the direct cause of 0% name accuracy.",\n      "fix": "Replace strategy.add_attribute_fuser(\\"name\\", maximum) with strategy.add_attribute_fuser(\\"name\\", prefer_higher_trust, trust_map={\\"metacritic\\": 3, \\"sales\\": 2, \\"dbpedia\\": 1}).",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Validation expects canonical game titles in mixed case with edition text preserved. Source comparison on matched records shows metacritic exact=65%, sales exact=35%, dbpedia exact=33%, all with 100% non-null coverage. That makes prefer_higher_trust the best resolver because one source is clearly superior. voting is worse because source disagreement is common and could select inferior forms when sales/dbpedia agree on a non-gold variant. longest_string/shortest_string are not supported by evidence; validation does not consistently prefer longer or shorter titles, and the current issue is missing values rather than verbosity differences. most_complete provides no advantage because all sources are already complete. A trust-ordered scalar resolver aligned to metacritic best matches the observed validation behavior.",\n      "class": "improvable",\n      "expected_impact": 0.125\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "platform",\n      "issue": "Residual wrong platform values remain, but current accuracy is already 70% and diagnostics classify this attribute as structurally limited under current matching structure.",\n      "fix": "Preserve the current platform resolver for now; do not change it in pipeline_adaption until name is fixed and re-evaluated.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Source comparison suggests sales is best for platform (70% exact), but the current recommendation from probes is voting(sales > dbpedia > metacritic), and changing this now risks regressing an attribute that is not catastrophically broken. Because pipeline_adaption changes only fusion and many mismatches likely stem from wrong cluster membership, resolver tweaks alone may provide only marginal gains. Fix the clearly broken name rule first, then reassess whether prefer_higher_trust or favour_sources toward sales outperforms voting on the updated clusters.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "developer",\n      "issue": "Developer is already at 90% accuracy and should be protected.",\n      "fix": "Keep strategy.add_attribute_fuser(\\"developer\\", prefer_higher_trust, trust_map=trust_map) unchanged.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Despite one mismatch example, the attribute is already above the protection threshold and near its apparent ceiling. Changing resolver or trust ordering here could regress a working attribute for little benefit.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "publisher",\n      "issue": "Publisher is already at 90% accuracy and should be protected.",\n      "fix": "No change.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Protected attribute; no evidence supports a safer better resolver than the current one.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "ESRB",\n      "issue": "ESRB is already at 90% accuracy and should be protected.",\n      "fix": "No change.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "Protected attribute with no demonstrated fusion failure pattern requiring intervention.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    },\n    {\n      "attribute": "criticScore",\n      "issue": "criticScore is already at 100% accuracy.",\n      "fix": "No change.",\n      "resolver_reasoning": "At ceiling; any change would only add regression risk.",\n      "class": "structurally_limited",\n      "expected_impact": 0.0\n    }\n  ]\n}\n            \n            Compact summary from the prior reasoning:\n            {\n  "root_cause": "The primary actionable defect is in fusion logic, sp